            <h3>1. Mount Kenya</h3>
            <img src="mt_kenya.jpeg">
            <p>Mount Kenya is the second highest mountain in Africa, standing tall at 5,199 meters. It is a popular destination for climbers and trekkers. The mountain features diverse landscapes, including glaciers, alpine meadows, and forests. The area is also home to wildlife such as elephants, buffaloes, and various bird species.</p>

            <h3>2. Maasai Mara National Reserve</h3>
            <img src="maasai_mara.jpeg" >
            <p>Maasai Mara is renowned for the annual Great Migration, where millions of wildebeest, zebras, and gazelles travel across the plains in search of fresh grazing. The reserve is also famous for its rich wildlife, including lions, leopards, cheetahs, and elephants, making it a top destination for safaris.</p>

            <h3>3. Lamu Island</h3>
            <img src="lamu_island.jpg" >
            <p>Lamu Island, located off the coast of Kenya, is known for its preserved Swahili culture and ancient architecture. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and offers a peaceful escape with its sandy beaches, historic towns, and traditional dhow sailing. The island is rich in history and has a vibrant local culture.</p>

            <h3>4. Lake Nakuru</h3>
            <img src="lake nakuru.jpg" >
            <p>Lake Nakuru is famous for its massive population of flamingos that gather along the shores, especially during the wet season. The lake is also home to a variety of wildlife, including black rhinos, white rhinos, giraffes, and lions. The surrounding Nakuru National Park is a great spot for a safari.</p>

            <h3>5. Amboseli National Park</h3>
            <img src="amboseli.jpg" >
            <p>Amboseli National Park is famous for its large herds of elephants and its breathtaking views of Mount Kilimanjaro, the highest peak in Africa. Visitors can enjoy a variety of wildlife, including lions, cheetahs, giraffes, and hippos, as well as stunning landscapes of savannah and wetlands.</p>

